    "narrative": "The Zurich Zebras enter April 14 with a clear focal point in **Yordan Alvarez**, who anchors the offense with a 76.36 score against Lorenzen. While his base projection is already formidable, his matchup is amplified by a strong platoon advantage and a favorable xwOBA of 0.393, making him our safest bet for RBI production. In the stolen base department\u2014our most critical category\u2014we are leaning into **Caleb Durbin** (63.77) and **Pete Crow-Armstrong** (64.41). Despite a -6% adjustment for hitting in the 8-hole, **Pete Crow-Armstrong** remains a must-start due to his elite speed profile, though his efficiency is tempered by an aggressive opponent catcher and a high-hold probability from the opposing staff. **Trea Turner** and **Kyle Schwarber** face a difficult test against the 0.00 xERA of Martin, but their order placement and the benefit of wind blowing out provide enough cushion to keep them as core contributors in our pursuit of 5x5 volume.\n\nThe most difficult decision on the bench was **Carson Benge**, who finished just a hair below our 40.0 floor at 39.80. While the platoon advantage against Yamamoto would typically warrant a look, his deployment in the 9-hole created an efficiency drag that necessitated a seat on the pine, especially with **Victor Scott II** clinging to a 40.70 score despite a tough matchup against Cantillo. We are monitoring the status of **Christian Yelich**, who remains sidelined, and continue to watch for updates on **Colt Keith** and **Zac Veen**, both of whom are currently unavailable to bolster our depth. Managers should note that while the wind is favorable for several hitters today, the matchup against elite arms like Ragans remains a significant risk for **Dillon Dingler**, whose scoring reflects the difficulty of facing a sub-3.00 xERA pitcher regardless of his spot in the batting order.",
